sections.english:
Monks, the uninstructed ordinary person speaks this saying: ‘There is an abyss in the great ocean.’ Indeed, monks, this uninstructed ordinary person speaks of what is not real, what does not exist, when he says: ‘There is an abyss in the great ocean.’ Indeed, monks, this term ‘abyss’ is a designation for bodily painful feelings. Monks, when an uninstructed ordinary person is afflicted by bodily painful feeling, he grieves, laments, weeps, beats his breast, and falls into utter confusion. This one, monks, is called ‘an uninstructed ordinary person who did not emerge from the abyss and did not find firm ground.’ However, monks, when an instructed noble disciple is afflicted by bodily painful feeling, he neither grieves, nor laments, nor weeps, nor beats his breast, nor falls into utter confusion. This one, monks, is called ‘an instructed noble disciple who emerged from the abyss and found firm ground.’

He who does not endure these painful feelings that have arisen,
Bodily, life-threatening, by which afflicted he trembles;

He cries out and weeps, weak and without strength;
He did not emerge from the abyss, nor did he find firm ground.

But he who endures these painful feelings that have arisen,
Bodily, life-threatening, by which afflicted he does not tremble;
He indeed emerged from the abyss, and indeed found firm ground.
